[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]THRESHOLDS FOR THE USE OF SCHEDULE 7 POWERS[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Legal background[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The Schedule 7 powers[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The c[bold]urrent threshold[bold]s[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]P[bold]owers to stop, question and search[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“
[normal]Schedule 7 powers are to be used solely for the pu
[normal]rpose of 
[normal]allowing for the determination of 
[normal]whether
[normal] the
[normal] person 
[normal]examined 
[normal]appears to be
[normal], or to have been, concerned in 
[normal]the commission,
[normal] 
[normal]preparation or instigation of acts of terrorism.  
[normal]The powers must not be used to stop and question persons for any other purpose.”
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The courts will no doubt continue, if necessary, to declare an examination unlawful on the basis that it was not used for the statutory purpose.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]P[bold]ower[bold] to [bold]detain[bold]              [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The examining officer considering (or a senior officer being satisfied) that detention is 
[normal]necessary in order to assist in determining[bold] whether a person appears to be 
[normal]a person falling within section 40(1)(b) [i.e. a 
[normal]person who is or has been concern
[normal]ed in the commission, preparation or instigation of acts of terrorism;]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The examining officer considering (or a senior officer being satisfied) that there are 
[normal]grounds for suspecting[bold] that the person appears to be 
[normal]a person falling within section 40(1)(b); or
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The examining officer considering (or a senior officer being satisfied) that there are 
[normal]reasonable grounds for suspecting[bold] that the person appears to be a person falling within section 40(1)(b). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The first 
[normal](“
[normal]necessary in order to assist in 
[normal]determining
[normal]”) 
[normal]is
[normal] 
[normal]little more than a statement of the obligation that rests upon any officer whose decision is liable to infringe the Article 8 (or Article 5) rights of another person.  It is based on the existing threshold for the taking of fingerprints or 
[normal]a 
[normal]DNA sample,
[normal] 
[normal]which the Government does not propose
[normal] to amend, 
[normal]and resembles the “
[normal]necessity
[normal]” threshold that the Bill proposes to introduce for 
[normal]authorisation by the review officer of 
[normal]continued 
[normal]detention after a so far unspecified period.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The second (“
[normal]grounds for suspecting
[normal]”)
[normal] would echo the subjective belief standards already present in paragraphs 2(2)(b) and 2(4) of Schedule 7.  It would require the officer to have formed a suspicion
[normal], 
[normal]whether on the basis of information supplied by others, behavioural assessment or even just intuition
[normal].  It would however
[normal] 
[normal]ensure that (in the words of Lord Bingham, in the conte
[normal]xt of a stop and search power) a ports officer
[normal] is not deterred from 
[normal]detaining 
[normal]“
[normal]a person whom he does suspect as a potential terrorist by the fear that he could not show reasonable grounds for his 
[normal]suspicion
[normal]”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The third (“
[normal]reasonable grounds for suspecting
[normal]”)
[normal] 
[normal]is the default threshold for most stop and search powers, and 
[normal]was 
[normal]the solution favoured
[normal] by the JCHR
[normal] in relation to the detention power
[normal].
[normal]  It is related to (though not identical to) the proposal in the Bill that strip searches should be conducted 
[normal]only where the examining officer has “
[normal]reasonable grounds to suspect that the person is concealing something which may be evidence that the person falls within section 40(1)(b)
[normal]”.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold](a)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Detention be permitted only when a senior officer is satisfied that [bold]there are grounds for suspecting that the[bold] person appears to be a person falling within section 40(1)(b)[bold] and that detention is necessary in order to assist in determining whether he is such a person[bold].[bold]&#xa0;[bold](b)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] On periodic review, a detention may be exten[bold]ded only when a senior officer remain[bold]s satisfied that there continue to b[bold]e grounds for suspecting that the person appears to be a person falling within section 40(1)(b)[bold], and that detention continues to be necessary in order to assist in determining whether he is such a person[bold].[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Copying and retention of[bold] electronic [bold]data[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]FURTHER [bold]SAFEGUARDS[bold]&#xa0;
[normal](a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Property may be detained for seven days, even in the absence of any belief that it may be needed for use as evidence in criminal proceedings or in connection with a deportation decision.  This contrasts with a period of 48 hours for the retention of documents obtained under reasonable suspicion powers such as section 43 of and Schedule 5 to the Terrorism Act 2000, subject to a single extension of up to a further 48 hours if an officer of at least the rank of chief inspector is satisfied that the examination is being carried out expeditiously, and that it is necessary to continue the examination to ascertain whether the document is one that may be seized.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Schedule 7 contain
[normal]s, as the JCHR has pointed out, no 
[normal]express 
[normal]system of safeguards for categories of material such as legally privileged material, excluded material and special procedure material
[normal] (including “
[normal]journalistic material
[normal]”).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The retention of electronic data is liable to be held for very long periods under the MOPI regime, which as I reported in July 2013 has been recently criticised in the courts.
[normal]  The system is in marked contrast to the rules and guidance that exist under the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012 concerning the retention and use of material (including biometric material gathered from Schedule 7 detainees) for the purposes of national security.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]USE OF EVIDENCE GIVEN UNDER COMPULSION[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“It is one thing to conclude that the Schedule 7 powers of examination neither engage nor violate a defendant’s Art. 6 rights; it is another to conclude that there is no room for improvement.  For our part, we would urge those concerned to consider a legislative amendment, introducing a statutory bar to the introduction of Schedule 7 admissions in a subsequent criminal trial.  The terms of any such legislation would require careful reflection, having regard to the legitimate interests of all parties but, given the sensitivities to which the Schedule 7 powers give rise, there would be at least apparent attraction in clarifying legislation putting the matter beyond doubt.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
